"Facts Precede Opinions states that content accepted by Wikipedians to be factual takes precedence over content that is contended to be opinionated." An article cannot be based primarily on tertiary and speculative sources, and opinions, while at the same time be absolutely silent about all actual historical evidence, which has left this article unbalanced.
added clause to introduction explaining their beliefs

Undid revision 847314202 by [[Special:Contributions/188.146.43.164|188.146.43.164]] ([[User talk:188.146.43.164|talk]]) This is not a blog; while this document may have been a wonderful resource to some, this type of advertisement does not belong in a Wikipedia article. Additionally, the document has been deleted.

I agree in hindsight with undoing the lengthy Lightfoot quotation. Respectfully, however, the text of John 21:20-24 does not say it was based on the written testimony of the beloved disciple. It says, referring to the beloved disciple, who reclined on Jesus' chest at supper, that "This disciple is the one who testifies to these events and has recorded them here." (See John 21:20-24 NLT). The demonstrative signifies the one (i.e. disciple) just mentioned.
/* New Testament author */ Corrected a misstatement that does not line up with the source text.
/* Challenges to Authorship */ Quotation by Lightfoot, references.
/* The Gospel of John */ Edited for flow. Minor corrections.

/* New Testament author */ Many references to Eusebius of Caesarea were either overplayed or underplayed and have been replaced with direct quotations; the article lacked almost all historical evidence and testimony but was heavy with speculative sources, making it unbalanced.
Added information on Caius of Rome
Scripture - Clarified statements that needed clarifying, added references that were lacking, and corrected statements according to the sources.

added reference. short unverifiable assertion removed.
/* Examination and Defense of Colwell's Rule in John 1:1 */
/* Examination and Defense of Colwell's Rule in John 1:1 */ References
/* Emphatic and Nuance-based Translations */ Source and quotation from Metzger on John 1:1
/* Common Objections */ Added quotation by Wallace regarding Acts 28:6
/* Examination and Defense of Colwell's Rule in John 1:1 */

/* Biblical parallels */ Bibleref2 used for references from the text, instead of from footnotes. One footnote has been moved into the text. DRA quotations have been replaced with equivalent English versions translated from the Greek, since the DRA was translated from the Latin rather than the Greek, and Greek words are being discussed.
/* Biblical parallels */ Added Colossians 1:15-18 and Hebrews 1:8-10
/* Common Objections */ Quotation added from Wallace regarding function of the article

/* Common Objections */ Acts 28:6 involves a double predicate accusative as the subject of an infinitive, which does not fall under Colwell's rule. Colwell's rule is to be applied to predicate nominatives.
/* Common Objections */ Tenses in quotations; written works should be referred to in the present.
/* Unitarian, Universalist, and Non-Trinitarian Translations */ Replaced summary of source with similarly worded quotation from the same source
/* Common Objections */ Included additional example verses
/* Common Objections */ Subsections added for better readability
/* John 1:1 in Translation */ Wallace misstates the converse of Colwell's rule as Colwell's rule; this is noted in contrast with Colwell's actual definition and treatment of John 1:1
/* John 1:1 in English versions */ More versions verified

/* John 1:1 in English versions */ Some quotations corrected. Original list of non-Trinitarian translations had evidently been taken from an anonymous list circulated online, some quotations upon verification were found to not accurately reproduce the source (missing brackets, changed punctuation, wrong wording, et al). Non-English versions removed.
/* John 1:1 in English versions */ Original spelling of older versions restored where possible.
/* Eschatology */ Made terminology consistent between Eschatology and Works attributed.
References. Clarified the anonymous section on Cerinthus's eschatology.
/* John 1:1 in English versions */ Refs. and links
/* History */ Added important testimony from Irenaeus, who was a student of one of John's disciples, and details the reasons why John wrote the preface to the gospel in the manner he did.
/* John 1:1 in English versions */ More versions
/* Source text and translations */ Ordering of the article for proper flow.

/* History */ Tertullian misquoted to give the appearance that he believes in two gods (which in the broader argument he is arguing against), using an IR Latin translation. The quotes have been replaced with established works, and are now in proper context of his argument.

One misquote and one misrepresentation of Origen's beliefs have been removed; by "second God" Origen is clear he does not mean another God beside the Father, but expresses that by it "we mean nothing else than a virtue capable of including all other virtues, and a reason capable of containing all reason whatsoever which exists in all things, which have arisen naturally, directly, and for the general advantage". In 8.12 of the same work, he writes "We worship one God, the Father and the Son"

/* Grammar */ Interpretations by Wallace et al. of Colwell's rule do not match what Colwell says, and should not be placed sequentially after Colwell's statement they are misrepresenting as to invalidate it. They have been placed now in proper sequence.
Colwell's rule stated in the translation section, instead of referenced only.
/* History */ Uncritical statement by Marcellus and embellishments on Valentinian beliefs corrected

/* Trinity */ Marcellus's uncorroborated testimony concerning Valentinus, which conflicts with other accounts of Valentinus's beliefs (as well as those of Plato and Hermes), was not only treated uncritically, but also embellished. This has been corrected to give a more critical view of his statements, which do not seem to reflect the actual beliefs of Valentinus.

/* References to Old Testament */ Removed a clearly biased statement, "There is no explicit reference to a historical person Jesus or to the concept of the atoning sacrificial death of the Son of God." Why would a Christian bishop of Antioch not believe in a historical person of Jesus, or his atoning sacrificial death? Fixed a misleading statement, "Theophilus makes no mention of . . . the phrase Son of God." While he does not use the phrase, he does plainly speak of the Logos as being God's Son
/* Trinity */ Noted second century identification of the Spirit as "Wisdom" (Sophia), eliminated a redundant sentance
/* John 1:1 (Translation) */ References. Expanded section on the reasoning behind Faust's translation
Expanded section on Psalm 33:6 with reference to other early Christian writers, such as Origen and Irenaeus
/* Theophilus of Antioch */ added "Patriarch of Antioch"
Added section on Athenagoras of Athens
Expanded the article with quotations from early Christin writers, added certain references where necessary. Some grammatical fixes and transitions worked on.
/* Christology */ Redundant statement and reference to Gordon Clark removed as irrelevant to Christology. Statement still occurs earlier on the page.
/* Christology */ "highest Christology of the gospels" is subjective. High Christology is sufficient.
/* Common Objections */ Restructured paragraphs according to topic/sources
Restored some wording from original version which divorced a statement from its proper source, probably through misunderstanding of what was being said.
/* Irenaeus of Lyon */ Tagged possible original research.
More editorial statements corrected. Notices added where citations are needed.
Editorial statements removed. Analysis of primary sources removed.
